      "transcript": "And Brapick just released new research on which jobs AI is actually replacing and which ones it could replace in theory.\nThey introduced this metric called observed exposure, which in the chart you can see the blue area showing what AI could\ntheoretically handle and the red area showing what it's actually handling today.\nFor example, in computer and math jobs, AI could theoretically handle about 94% tasks,\nbut Claude is currently only covering about 33% of those in practice.\nSimilar story for office and admin roles with about 90% of tasks theoretically,\nautomatable, but actually you should today just a fraction of that.\nSo it's pretty clear that AI adoption is still very much so in its early days.\nAnd if you look at the top 10 most exposed occupations base off of this observed exposure metric,\nthe number one is computer programmers with about 74.5% exposure.\nAnd that tracks of everything we're seeing around AI coding right now.\nThen you have customer service reps at 70% data entry workers 67% medical records specialist 66%\nand you can read through the restless, but you even have financial and investment analysts up there at 57%.\nOne of the pretty clear themes here is that all of these are knowledge work jobs.\nThey're relatively well paid and they often require higher education.\nIn fact, the most AI exposed group in the study is generally more educated, higher paid,\nand also 16% more likely to be female, which means that the workers most\nexposed to AI today are actually the very people who went through higher ed and pursued white\ncolor careers, partly to avoid the kind of automation that hit manufacturing and the trade\ndecades ago. At the same time, it is important to keep in mind a few caveats here.\nThis study combines real cloud usage data with estimates of what AI could theoretically do,\nso it's not necessarily a perfect prediction of jobless. On top of this,\nendropics says that despite the exposure numbers were not seeing mass unemployment yet.\nTheir researchers actually compared workers in highly AI exposed jobs and workers in AI\nresistant jobs, and the difference in unemployment since the release of CHAPBT is basically\nstatistically zero. So the feared AI job blockalyps that this report lays out\nhasn't shown up in the data, at least not yet."
